<font color="#FF0000">REPLIES TO ALL ABOVE</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb  8 13:01:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
After sitting on the sidelines for some time, felt I should jump in.<br><br>
1. In March of 1969, I sent a poem from my base in Vietnam to the student newspaper at Marquette U. A letter came back 2 weeks later with no word on whether the poem was good, bad, or indifferent, but simply stated. &quot;How dare a baby killer like you assume to write poetry.&quot;  About a month later, my btother sustained a knee injury defending the ROTC office at U Wisconsin-Milwaukee from an attempted takeover/sitin that ended his ROTC enrollment.  Upon arrival at Oakland Army Depot in mid-July, was instructed in no uncertain terms that  all of us were NOT to travel in uniform but in civvies.<br><br>
2. In case anybody forgot, Nixon was supposedly committed to ending the war when he ran in 1968.  After 3 1/2 years, he got about the same deal available when he took office.<br><br>
3. Yes, the Gulf War was about OIL, but it was also about not allowing a bully to extinguish a country's existence, the form of government in Kuwait being irrelevant here.<br><br>
4. The visceral anti-Communism of many Americans cannot be ignored as part of why we went into Vietnam.  This strain in  American politics and culture goes back at least to the Haymarket riots and anarchist scares of the early 1890's and the Palmer raids following WWI.  I grew up in Wisconsin in the '50's and remember dozens of horrible arguments between my Dad and my grandfather over Sen. Joe McCarthy.  The John Birch Society was founded during this period in Wisconsin.  Not only ultra-conservatives were worried about Communists. Many communities refused to floridate their water because it was a &quot;Communist Plot&quot;.  Not to excuse it, but getting militarily involved in Vietnam was a natural extension of not only American policy, but deep seated beliefs and fears in the AMerican people from the late '40's thru the '50's.<br><br>
5. Yo, people!  Anybody who insists that all the motives were &quot;pure as the driven snow&quot; or &quot;rotten as a truckload of ten year old elephant dung&quot; is trying to put events in a nice, neat, and totally non-existent little box.  As the imperfect people all human beings are; American foreign policy and military action is a maddeningly contadictory mess of good and bad motives and reasons, often with the right thing being done for the wrong reason and the wrong thing being done for the right reason.  To attempt to put all the reasons for a given action on one side of the ledger<br>
to justify oneself, is to usually ignore a key piece of contradictory evidence because it doesn't &quot;fit&quot;.  One makes the best moral choice one can, with the understanding that someone else may decide differently.  One may even have to fight the other party sometime, but feeling obliged to do so does not guarantee one's moral superiority.  It is quite possible both may be in large part wrong.  The Vietnam War bore some rather ugly fruit for both sides. <br>

<p><code>-- turtle@plantaganet.com  (Gerald Ney, the Herd-7/68 7/69) </code><p>


